	<item>
		<title>Understanding Dependency Injection</title>
		<link>https://example.com/?p=20</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 12 Feb 2025 09:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[janewriter]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://example.com/?p=20</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Dependency Injection (DI) is a design pattern that promotes loose coupling between components. This article covers the fundamentals.</p>

<h2>What is Dependency Injection?</h2>
<p>Instead of creating dependencies inside a class, they are "injected" from outside — typically through the constructor.</p>

<h2>Benefits</h2>
<ul>
<li>Easier testing with mock objects</li>
<li>Better separation of concerns</li>
<li>More flexible and reusable code</li>
</ul>

<p>We'll continue this series with practical examples using PHP-DI.</p>]]></content:encoded>
		<excerpt:encoded><![CDATA[Learn the fundamentals of Dependency Injection and how it promotes better software architecture.]]></excerpt:encoded>
